SIMPLE: signet
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Signet
<hw>Sig"net</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>signet</ets>
a signet, F., a bookmark, dim. of <ets>signe</ets>. See <er>Sign</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, and cf. <er>Sennet</er>.]</ety> <def>A seal; especially,
in England, the seal used by the sovereign in sealing private letters
and grants that pass by bill under the sign manual; -- called also
<altname>privy signet</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I had my father's <qex>signet</qex> in my purse.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Signet ring</b></col>, <cd>a ring containing a signet or
private seal.</cd> -- <col><b>Writer to the signet</b></col> <fld>(Scots
Law)</fld>, <cd>a judicial officer who prepares warrants, writs, etc.;
originally, a clerk in the office of the secretary of
state.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Signeted</ent>⟦br⟧
